{"cursor":"50694","size":15,"audio":["http://www.suttareadings.net/audio/dhp.01.gfro.mp3"],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Buddhist term |float=right |pi= |sa= |my=ááá¹áááºáá¾ááºáá«á¸ |my-Latn=mÉÊÉ¡ÉªÌÉ´ ÊÉªÊ pÃ¡\n|zh= |zh-Latn=BÄzhÃ¨ngdÃ o |ja= |ja-Latn=HasshÅdÅ |ko= |ko-Latn=Paljeongdo |th=\n|th-Latn=Ariya Mugg Paad |mn=qutuÎ³tan-u naiman gesigÃ¼n-Ã¼ mÃ¶r |title= The Noble\nEightfold Path }}\n\n, often used to represent the Noble Eightfold Path]]\n\nThe 'Noble Eightfold Path' (}}, {{lang-sa|}}) Brekke, Torkel. \"The Religious\nMotivation of the Early Buddhists.\" Journal of the American Academy of Religion,\nVol. 67, No. 4 (Dec., 1999), p. 860 is one of the principal [[Dharma\n(Buddhism)|teachings]] of [[Gautama Buddha|the Buddha]], who described it as the\nway leading to the cessation of suffering (dukkha) and the achievement of self-\nawakening. {{cite\nweb|url=http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/sn/sn56/sn56.011.than.html\n|title=Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta |accessdate=2008-05-06|publisher=Access to\nInsight |last=Thanissaro Bhikkhu}} It is used to develop insight into the\ntrue nature of phenomena (or reality) and to eradicate greed, hatred, and\ndelusion. The Noble Eightfold Path is the fourth of the Buddha's [[Four Noble\nTruths]]; the first element of the Noble Eightfold Path is, in turn, an\nunderstanding of the Four Noble Truths. It is also known as theMiddle\nPathorMiddle Way''.\n\nAll eight elements of the Path begin with the word \"right\", which translates the\nword samyaÃ±c (in Sanskrit) or sammÄ (in PÄli). These denote completion,\ntogetherness, and coherence, and can also suggest the senses of \"perfect\" or\n\"ideal\". See, for instance, [http://www.buddhanet.net/e-\nlearning/8foldpath.htm Allan (2008).] 'Samma' is also translated as\n\"wholesome\", \"wise\" and \"skillful\".\n\nIn Buddhist symbolism, the Noble Eightfold Path is often represented by means of\nthe dharma wheel (dharmachakra), whose eight spokes represent the eight elements\nof the path.\n","linknr":971,"url":"Noble_eightfold_path","recorded":1374780666,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Noble_Eightfold_Path&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Noble_Eightfold_Path&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Noble_Eightfold_Path","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Noble_eightfold_path&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Eightfold_Path_(disambiguation)","/wiki/Pali","/wiki/Sanskrit","/wiki/Burmese_language","/wiki/Help:IPA_for_Burmese","/wiki/Chinese_language","//zh.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%85%AB%E6%AD%A3%E9%81%93","/wiki/Pinyin","/wiki/Japanese_language","//ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E5%85%AB%E6%AD%A3%E9%81%93","/wiki/R%C5%8Dmaji","/wiki/Korean_language","//ko.wikipedia.org/wiki/%ED%8C%94%EC%A0%95%EB%8F%84","/wiki/Revised_Romanization_of_Korean","/wiki/Mongolian_language","/wiki/Thai_language","//th.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E0%B8%A1%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%84%E0%B8%A1%E0%B8%B5%E0%B8%AD%E0%B8%87%E0%B8%84%E0%B9%8C%E0%B9%81%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%94","/wiki/Glossary_of_Buddhism","/wiki/Category:Buddhism","/wiki/Buddhism","/wiki/Dharmacakra","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Dharma_Wheel.svg/100px-Dharma_Wheel.svg.png","/wiki/History_of_Buddhism","/wiki/Timeline_of_Buddhism","/wiki/G